<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,374,508,534]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Observations:</emphasis>
—In the SEM the valve has irregular areolae that occur across the face (
<figureCitation box="[1242,1428,508,534]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Figs 2–A, B, C</figureCitation>
) and extend onto the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[495,604,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2–E</figureCitation>
). Two, rarely three (
<figureCitation box="[848,956,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2–B</figureCitation>
) ocelli are present. Ocelli are ellipticalelongate in shape and the porelli that comprise the ocelli are small and radiate in their organization (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Figs 2–A, B, F</figureCitation>
). Internally, ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face/mantle junction (
<figureCitation box="[1113,1265,625,651]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Figs 2–C, D</figureCitation>
). Rimportulae have round openings externally (
<figureCitation box="[533,679,663,689]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Figs 2–A, B</figureCitation>
). Internally they are elevated and lip-like (
<figureCitation box="[1175,1320,663,689]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Figs 2–G, H</figureCitation>
). There is a c–shaped depression around the rimportula internally (Fig. H). The girdle is wide, and copulae possess distinct pores.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName box="[198,402,779,804]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis box="[198,402,779,804]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Pleurosira indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ehrenb.) Compere" authorityName="Compere" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenb." box="[556,885,779,805]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="laevis">
<emphasis box="[556,656,779,804]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">P.laevis</emphasis>
(Ehrenb.) Compère
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of irregularly arranged areolae and presence of c–shaped depression around the rimoportulae. 
<taxonomicName box="[883,1082,818,843]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="laevis">
<emphasis box="[883,1082,818,843]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Pleurosira laevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1098,1167,818,844]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,255,2009,2033]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,874,1995]" captionTargetId="figure-223@2.[151,1436,874,1995]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pleurosira indica LM. Valves showing the size diminution series. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776712" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776712/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1152,1167,818,844]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" unit="in" value="1.0">1</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Compere, P." box="[1203,1378,818,844]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" pagination="165 - 190" refId="ref5508" refString="Compere, P. (1982) Taxonomic revision of the Diatom genus Pleurosira (Eupodiscaceae). Bacillaria 5: 165 - 190." type="journal article" year="1982">Compère 1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,257,1840,1864]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetId="figure-135@3.[151,1436,185,1813]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Pleurosira indica SEM. A. External view of the valve showing the irregular areolae across the face. B. External view of the valve with 3 ocelli. C&amp;D. Internal view of the valve showing the ocelli appear as depressions at the valve face and mantle junction. E. External girdle view shows the areolae extend onto the mantle. F. External view of the ocelli. G.Internal view of the valve shows the different folding nature of the rimoportulae with areolae. H. Internal view of the view shows the c-shaped depression around the rimportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, B, C, E: 10 µm; Fig. D: 5 µm; Fig. F: 2 µm; Figs. G, H: 1µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4776714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4776714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Fig. 2–A</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kociolek, J. P. &amp; Lamb, M. A. &amp; Lowe, R. L." box="[238,477,857,883]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" pagination="125 - 130" refId="ref7153" refString="Kociolek, J. P., Lamb, M. A. &amp; Lowe, R. L. (1983) Notes on the growth and ultrastructure of Biddulphia laevis Ehr. (Bacillariophyceae) in the Maumee River, Ohio. Ohio Journal of Science 83: 125 - 130." type="journal article" year="1983">
Kociolek 
<emphasis box="[352,410,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">et al.</emphasis>
1983
</bibRefCitation>
) shows a clear pattern in areolae arrangement with striae radiating from the centre to margin and a silica surface which separate the porelli from areolae (
<figureCitation box="[980,1050,895,921]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,257,1834,1858]" captionText="FIGURE 4. Spicaticribra kodaikanaliana SEM. A. External view of the valve face. B. External view of the valve mantle. C. External view of the valve face showing the siliceous nodules scattered across the periphery of the valve. D. Detailed view of the siliceous nodules on the valve periphery. E&amp;F Tilted valve showing three pores on each fultoportula. G. Internal view of the valve with pore field radiating from valve center with structures of fultoportula. Scale bars: Figs. A, C, G: 2 µm; Figs. B, D, E, F: 1µm" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1035,1050,895,921]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" unit="in" value="4.0">4</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Compere, P." box="[1088,1263,895,921]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" pagination="165 - 190" refId="ref5508" refString="Compere, P. (1982) Taxonomic revision of the Diatom genus Pleurosira (Eupodiscaceae). Bacillaria 5: 165 - 190." type="journal article" year="1982">Compère 1982</bibRefCitation>
) is also absent in 
<emphasis box="[182,512,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName box="[182,290,934,959]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="indica">P. indica</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[303,512,934,959]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="indica">Pleurosira indica</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Compere" authorityName="Compere" box="[918,1366,934,960]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="variety" species="soctrensis" variety="pangeroni">
<emphasis box="[918,1071,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">P. soctrensis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1128,1249,934,959]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">pangeroni</emphasis>
Compère
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 33–36, 44 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Compere, P." box="[308,484,972,998]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" pagination="165 - 190" refId="ref5508" refString="Compere, P. (1982) Taxonomic revision of the Diatom genus Pleurosira (Eupodiscaceae). Bacillaria 5: 165 - 190." type="journal article" year="1982">Compère 1982</bibRefCitation>
) by valve outline and absence of a c–shaped depression around each rimportula. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,590,1011,1037]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="variety" species="soctrensis" variety="pangeroni">
<emphasis box="[151,406,1011,1036]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Pleurosira soctrensis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[468,590,1011,1036]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">pangeroni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been reported from South 
<collectingCountry box="[1024,1085,1011,1037]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">India</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Compere, P." box="[1102,1287,1011,1037]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" pagination="165 - 190" refId="ref5508" refString="Compere, P. (1982) Taxonomic revision of the Diatom genus Pleurosira (Eupodiscaceae). Bacillaria 5: 165 - 190." type="journal article" year="1982">Compère 1982</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Pleurosira indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from another Indian taxon, 
<taxonomicName authority="Compere" authorityName="Compere" authorityYear="1982" box="[699,1278,1050,1076]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Triceratiaceae" genus="Pleurosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Triceratiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="variety" species="socotrensis" variety="bengalensis">
<emphasis box="[699,962,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">Pleurosira socotrensis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1022,1161,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="29">bengalensis</emphasis>
Compère
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 37, 38, 
<quantity box="[151,211,1089,1115]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1176" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" unit="in" value="44.0">44 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Compere, P." box="[218,394,1089,1115]" pageId="4" pageNumber="29" pagination="165 - 190" refId="ref5508" refString="Compere, P. (1982) Taxonomic revision of the Diatom genus Pleurosira (Eupodiscaceae). Bacillaria 5: 165 - 190." type="journal article" year="1982">Compère 1982</bibRefCitation>
), by the absence of the 6–15 labiate processes being arranged in a circular fashion.
</paragraph>
